               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1443" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1443" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1443" type="surname" value="STOCKEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1443" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES STOCKEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am potman at the Craven Arms, Queen's-road, Bays<lb></lb>water. I missed a pair of blucher boots from the top of a beer-tray in the yard—they were safe a little before ten o'clock—I saw the prisoner in the tap-room that day after three o'clock—about six o'clock I taw the prisoner and John King together—King had got the boots—I asked the prisoner how he came by them—he said, "A man gave them to me crossing the fields."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1444" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1444" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1444" type="surname" value="KING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1444" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN KING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a potman at the Oraren Arms. I saw the prisoner in the tap-room—he had a flag basket with him—he went out—I afterwards beard Stocken had lost his boots—I met the prisoner in Queen's-road with the boots concealed under his jacket—I asked what he had got—he said, nothing belonging to me—I asked him to give me the boots—he said, "I have got no boots"—I said, "Let me look"—he unbuttoned his jacket, and took the boots out—I said, "They are not mine, they are my fellow-servant's"—he said, "B—your eyes, if you don't let go of me I will smash you"—I let go, but being surrounded with a mob of people he could not go—he was 100 or 200 yards from the Craven Arms—the boots were ten or twelve yards from the tap-room close to the bar parlour window.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I said if you came with me I would show you who gave them me. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> No, you said you would show me the man that gave you the handkerchief.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1445" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1445" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1445" type="surname" value="LODDER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1445" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN LODDER</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable D</hi> 207.) I took the prisoner into custody—he was not much the worse for liquor—King delivered the boots to me—the prisoner tried to get away, but tome people came to my assistance—he tried to kick my legs.</p>
               <p>(<hi rend="italic">Property produced and sworn to.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner 11 Defence.</hi> A man in the Craven Arms bought half a gallon of beer; after I drank, I went to sleep, and never awoke till ten minutes after five o'clock; the men were then all gone out; just outside the door, I met one of them, named Peter Ashburn; he said, "<hi rend="italic">Jack</hi>, if you <hi rend="italic">go</hi> across the field you will find an old pair of boots in the hedge, and we will have some more beer," which I did.</p>
